While getting my z height correct and playing around with different bed materials, I found myself constantly adjusting the z endstop.  If I tried to leave it loose enough to move, it didn't stay in place, and if it was too tight I couldn't move it.
I needed to be able to adjust it very small amounts to get the z-height just right to get a nice first layer that wasn't too hard to peel off, but still stuck.
This minor improvement does the trick.

Materials: a longish bolt, a spring, and a nut. The longer the bolt the more adjustment room you'll have, but you really don't need more than 1 1/2"-2".
Drill a hole somewhat larger than the bolt diameter in x-carriage just above mechanical endstop lever arm.  
Insert screw though spring from the top, and nut on the bottom. 
Coarsely get mechanical end-stop into position, adjust bolt down until it's near the lever arm.
Now you can get the nozzle nearly above the bed (I was told 1/2x the filament diameter), then screw the bolt down until it just triggers the end-stop.
Tighten the end-stop well, you won't need to move it again.
Enjoy being able to micro-adjust your z-endstop height.
This would be fairy easy to incorporate in the carriage files directly, with a hole for the nut.  Without something to hold the nut, you may need to apply pressure to it as you turn the screw, or you can glue the nut into place.

This is a model of the Space Shuttle that stands over 12" high. It started out as this model from Google's 3D warehouse. http://sketchup.google.com/3dwarehouse/details?mid=4c41b6547d241ffd9aa9d7f676c1fd7e&prevstart=0 All the parts come apart so you can configure it in many ways.

  • On the launch pad fully assembled

  • Launched with boosters attached

  • Boosters detached - just the Orbiter and fuel tank

  • Orbiter by itself

Print, print and then print some more!  
Tallest piece is about 115mm and the launch pad takes up nearly the entire build platform of a Thing-O-Matic.  
Printed with a layer height of .25mm, 0 extra shells and 10% infill. You may want to print the launch pad with extra shells to increase the strength of the posts.  
Each of the main parts, the Orbiter, boosters and fuel tank are comprised of three pieces each which are pinned together using bits of 3mm filament and glued. Gluing is optional, but recommended. I use acetone.  
Attach the Orbiter to the fuel tank using 3mm filament. If the filament fits too loosely you can crush it slightly with pliers to make it wider. Attach the boosters to the fuel tank in the same manner.  
The engine piece snaps into the back of the Orbiter and the nozzle pieces for the boosters press into place. A bit of sanding may be needed depending upon how flared out the bottom gets printed.  
Enjoy!

title: Modular FPV camera mount for 25 mm tube

description.text:
An FPV camera mount for a 25 mm OD tube. Comes in 2 versions
  • a 3 component with housing, lens hood and long retainer clip.
  • a 2 component with housing and short retainer clip.
    • 3-component features:
  • can be to a 25 mm carbon tube using a plastic clamp.
  • Slots for lock-nuts for securing clamp.
  • Interchangable lenshood without removing housing or camera from housing. Supplied lens-hood is made for a 2.8 mm lens.
  • Tool-less change of camera or lens-hood, just release the retainer-clip
  • Perfect fit for a 30x31x11 mm FPV camera, like Foxtech WDR750 or similar
  • Cable stress relief/vibration killer using a 2-3 mm zip-tie.
    • 2-component features:
  • Same as 3-component, but without the lens-hood.
  • Lighter and simpler

3-component:
Download housing, hood and long retainer clip 2- component:
Download housing and short retainer clip I had success with everything from 0.05 mm to 0.2 mm layer height. It is important to print with a fairly high line-width, like 0.5 mm, and relatively high temperature to get the layers to stick properly to each other. If they do not stick, you will have problems with the lock-nuts breaking the layers apart.
Print with std 2 or 3 wall thickness. The lens hood should be printed in black, and sanded matte on the inside, so it doesn't relfect sunlight,

This things helps for adjusting the y-axis to be square with the x-axis on the K8200/3DRag.  
Take this at your own risk.

Ensure having the horizontal frame to be square.
Adjust the x-axis first. That's simple. Print a pair of the helper tool.
Put them on the rods and push them against the (left) rod blocks. These blocks will be covered by the printed parts then. Take a pair of identical sized AA-batteries (discharged) .
From the factory two from the same batch have identical length.
  • To be double safe check the length with a (digital) caliper.
    I have measured batteries from different vendors. I'v found them at various diameter round about 14mm. Some are wider others smaller. Find a pair of batteries matching the holes. The shape of the printed parts allows a small deviation from the ideal diameter. Don't press the batteries very hard. Better widen the holes a little by hand when needed.
    • Put the batteries in the holes and push them against the rod mounts. As usual flip the chassis, push the y-axis wagon slightly against the batterie poles, use them as stops. Don't clamp the wagon with the outer aluminium frame..
    This will not help. Note:
    The y-chassis was made from very soft flexing aluminium plate.
    Tighten all the screws subsequently. Find the right way.
    Be aware, fastening one screw after the other may reposition the wagon again.
    A small bit of tilting the y-plate away from being in parallel with the left aluminum extrusion may be needed at the beginning.
    If you are not satisfied after tigthening all screws , start over.

For advice on printing and painting see 'instructions' page. Feel free to scale it to your liking. Follow me on Twitter: @Realbrianbyrne
    See my web design website: http://www.sumbodesign.com I do not claim to own any copyright over this little droid! This is simply fan art. Big thanks to lilykill for original upload. Base is also compatible with his model.

1) Optional: When printing 'Stand', print with white up to when the stand starts curving, then pause print and replace filament with orange, then continue print.
2) On 'Stand', lightly paint over the 'Star Wars' logo with white.

description.text:
Based on A.R. design at http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:415761 but completely redrawn from scratch. This bobbin is designed to be printed as one piece horizontally. This is due to weaknesses inherent to printing cylinders vertically. For me, the other one stretched and broke the spool while winding. Since this is printed horizontally instead of vertically, the weakness on the spool is no longer present. This spool is also 2mm shorter than A.R.'s design to allow for stretching so that it still fits in the core. I have included a file with supports. Order it printed by Shapeways at http://shpws.me/Me49 Use with ferrite core UY1658:
